Short Course Description & Objectives

Provides a hands-on introduction to the R programming language. Prepares you with the fundamental programming skills required for today's OR analysts.


Upon successfully completing this course, you will:

  • Be up and running with R
  • Understand the different types of data R can work with
  • Understand the different structures in which R holds data
  • Be able Import data into R
  • Perform basic data wrangling activities with R
  • Compute basic descriptive statistics with R
  • Visualize their data with base R and ggplot graphics


All required classroom material can be downloaded from the course website:
http://afit-r.github.io/oper200

Analytics & Programming

Why Program?

Why Program?

Flexibility

  • Frees us from point-n-click analysis software
  • Allows us to customize our analyses
  • Allows us to build analytic applications

Slows us down

  • Forces us to think about our analytic processes

Speeds the analysis up

  • Many statistical programming languages now leverage C++ and Java to speed up computation time

Reproducibility

  • Provides reproducibility that spreadsheet analysis cannot
  • Literate statistical programming is on the rise

Programming is like kicking yourself in the face, sooner or later your nose will bleed.

  • Kyle Woodbury

Installation

  1. Go to https://cran.r-project.org/
  2. Click "Download R for Mac/Windows"
  3. Download the appropriate file:
    • Windows users click Base, and download the installer for the latest R version
    • Mac users select the file R-3.X.X.pkg that aligns with your OS version
  4. Follow the instructions of the installer.

  1. Go to RStudio for desktop https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/
  2. Select the install file for your OS
  3. Follow the instructions of the installer.

Note: Visit http://bit.ly/2bTJ6Op for more details on installation instructions for personal and AFIT computers.

Demo Time!


Your Turn - #1


Set your working directory to the "OPER 200" folder you downloaded or created for this course.

Your Turn - #2

Economic Order Quantity Model: \[Q = \sqrt \frac{2DK}{h}\]


Calculate Q where:

  • D = 1000
  • K = 5
  • h = 0.25

hint: sqrt(x) \(= \sqrt x\)

Basic Data Types

Vector

Your Turn - #3


1. type gallons <- readRDS("data/gallons.rds) in your console

2. what type of data does this vector contain?

3. how many observations are in the vector

4. what are the names of the vector

5. Remove gallons from your global environment

Vector Indexing



Your Turn - #4


1. load gallons back into your environment

2. index for the 3rd-5th elements

3. index for aircrafts 12, 17, 38

4. index for elements greater than 50M

Your Turn - #5

Back to our EOQ Model: \(Q = \sqrt \frac{2DK}{h}\)


1. Calculate Q for 3 items where:

  • \(D_1 = 900\), \(D_2 = 1000\), \(D_3 = 1450\)
  • \(K_1 = 5.5\), \(K_2 = 5\), \(K_3 = 4.5\)
  • \(h_1 = 0.25\), \(h_2 = 0.50\), \(h_3 = 0.75\)


2. What is the mean of Q?

Factors

2. what type of data does this vector contain?

3. turn this into an ordered factor with low < middle < high

4. how many observations are there for each level?
